When a user installs a large TTC file and opens our webpage, OOM will appear.
Through debugging, we found that the following method of using @font-face will create an sk_sp<SkTypeface> instance and load the font file once for each size of text, which will consume a lot of virtual memory.
```
@font-face {
       font-family: MyCustomFont;
       font-weight: 300;
       src: local("PingFangSC-Light");
}
```
Reproduction steps:
1. Install PingFang.ttc
2. Use 32-bit chromium to open font.html
3. Create a dmp file for the corresponding Render process.
4. Use a tool similar to windbg to analyze the MEM_MAPPED type of memory in the dmp file.


By analyzing the code, we found that `sk_sp<SkTypeface>` in the above demo was created using `AlternateFontName::kLocalUniqueFace`. Can we cache the `sk_sp<SkTypeface>` created through `AlternateFontName::kLocalUniqueFac`e in `FontCache`? This avoids creating the `sk_sp<SkTypeface>` object multiple times.
